    summaryEn: 'Founded under Gupta Emperor Kumaragupta I, Nalanda was the largest Buddhist center of learning in the ancient world, attracting scholars from across Asia with a library of nine million manuscripts.',
    description: '公元5世纪，笈多王朝的鸠摩罗笈多一世建立了那烂陀寺，它迅速发展为古代世界最负盛名的大学。寺院占地广大，建筑宏伟，拥有数百座讲堂、宿舍、寺庙和一座九层图书馆。来自印度、中国、中亚、东南亚的数千名僧侣学者在此研习佛教哲学、逻辑学、语言学、医学、天文学和数学。唐代高僧玄奘曾在此留学五年（631-636），带回大量佛经。该校持续繁荣近八百年，直到约1193年被突厥军队摧毁，标志着印度佛教的衰落。2014年，那烂陀大学在现代印度重建。',
    descriptionEn: 'In the 5th century CE, Gupta Emperor Kumaragupta I established Nalanda, which grew into the ancient world\'s most renowned university. The sprawling campus contained hundreds of lecture halls, dormitories, temples, and a nine-story library. Thousands of monks and scholars from India, China, Central Asia, and Southeast Asia studied Buddhist philosophy, logic, linguistics, medicine, astronomy, and mathematics here. The Tang-era Chinese monk Xuanzang studied at Nalanda for five years (631-636), bringing back a vast collection of scriptures. The institution flourished for nearly eight centuries until it was destroyed by Turkic forces around 1193, marking the decline of Buddhism in India. Nalanda University was reestablished in modern India in 2014.',
