    summaryEn: 'The Ghurid general Qutb-ud-din Aibak established the Muslim Sultanate in Delhi, ruling northern India for over three centuries and inaugurating the Indo-Islamic cultural synthesis.',
    description: '1206年，古尔王朝的突厥将领库特布丁·艾巴克在穆罕默德·古尔死后宣布独立，在德里建立了马穆鲁克（奴隶）王朝，这是德里苏丹国的第一个王朝。此后三百余年间，五个伊斯兰王朝（马穆鲁克、卡尔吉、图格鲁克、萨伊德、洛迪）先后以德里为中心统治印度北部。德里苏丹国时期，伊斯兰教在北印度扎根，波斯语成为官方语言，涌现了融合印度和伊斯兰风格的新建筑（库特布塔、苏丹加希）和文学。苏丹国成功抵御了蒙古人的多次入侵，保护了印度次大陆免受蒙古帝国的毁灭。不过，其对印度教寺庙的破坏和宗教政策也种下了次大陆长期宗教冲突的历史根源。',
    descriptionEn: 'In 1206, the Ghurid Turkic general Qutb-ud-din Aibak declared independence following the death of Muhammad of Ghor, founding the Mamluk (Slave) dynasty at Delhi—the first of the Delhi Sultanate. Over the next three centuries, five Islamic dynasties (Mamluk, Khalji, Tughlaq, Sayyid, Lodi) ruled northern India from Delhi. Under the Sultanate, Islam took deep root in northern India, Persian became the language of administration, and new architecture blending Indian and Islamic styles emerged (Qutb Minar, Sultan Ghari). The Sultanate successfully repelled multiple Mongol invasions, shielding the subcontinent from Mongol destruction. However, its destruction of Hindu temples and religious policies sowed the seeds of the subcontinent\'s long-term communal conflicts.',
