    summary: '教皇亚历山大六世调停下，西葡两国划定了新世界殖民地的分界线，深刻影响了美洲和亚洲的殖民格局与语言分布。',
    summaryEn: 'Under Pope Alexander VI\'s mediation, Spain and Portugal drew a line dividing the New World, profoundly shaping colonial patterns and linguistic distribution in the Americas and Asia.',
    description: '1494年6月7日，在教皇亚历山大六世的调停下，西班牙和葡萄牙在西班牙小镇托尔德西里亚斯签订条约，在大西洋中划分了一条从北极到南极的"教皇子午线"。线以西（美洲大部）归西班牙，线以东（非洲、亚洲和巴西东部）归葡萄牙。这就是为什么巴西说葡萄牙语而拉丁美洲其他国家说西班牙语的根源。1512年，麦哲伦环球航行后，两国又以《萨拉戈萨条约》（1529）在东半球划定了类似的界线，将香料群岛（摩鹿加群岛）等争议地带纳入条约体系。这两份条约为早期欧洲殖民时代划定了基本框架，其影响至今仍在全球语言、文化和政治版图中清晰可见。',
    descriptionEn: 'On June 7, 1494, under the mediation of Pope Alexander VI, Spain and Portugal signed the Treaty of Tordesillas, drawing a "Papal Line of Demarcation" from pole to pole through the Atlantic. Lands west of the line (most of the Americas) went to Spain; lands east (Africa, Asia, and eastern Brazil) to Portugal. This is why Brazil speaks Portuguese while the rest of Latin America speaks Spanish. Following Magellan\'s circumnavigation, the two powers drew a similar anti-meridian in the Eastern Hemisphere through the Treaty of Zaragoza (1529), bringing the Spice Islands (Moluccas) into the framework. These two treaties defined the basic structure of early European colonialism, and their effects remain clearly visible in global linguistic, cultural, and political maps today.',
