    importance: 5,
    summary: '财政危机迫使路易十六召开中断175年的三级会议，第三等级的抗议和网球场宣誓直接引爆了法国大革命。',
    summaryEn: 'Financial crisis forced Louis XVI to summon the Estates General after 175 years, and the Third Estate\'s protests and subsequent Tennis Court Oath directly ignited the French Revolution.',
    description: '1789年5月5日，因严重的财政危机，法王路易十六被迫在凡尔赛宫召开自1614年以来从未召集过的三级会议。会议分三个等级：教士（第一等级）、贵族（第二等级）和平民（第三等级，占人口97%）。第三等级代表要求按人头而非等级投票，遭到国王拒绝。6月17日，第三等级代表宣布自己为"国民议会"。三天后，当代表们发现会议厅被锁，便转至附近的室内网球场，在拜伊的主持下庄严宣誓："在宪法制定并以坚实基砥确立之前，决不解散"——这就是著名的"网球场宣誓"。这些事件标志着法国大革命的正式开始。',
    descriptionEn: 'On May 5, 1789, due to a severe financial crisis, Louis XVI was forced to summon the Estates General at Versailles for the first time since 1614. The assembly was organized into three estates: the Clergy (First Estate), the Nobility (Second Estate), and the Commoners (Third Estate, representing 97% of the population). The Third Estate demanded voting by head rather than by estate, which the king refused. On June 17, the Third Estate declared itself the "National Assembly." Three days later, finding their meeting hall locked, the deputies moved to a nearby indoor tennis court where, under Jean-Sylvain Bailly\'s chairmanship, they swore a solemn oath "never to separate until the constitution of the kingdom is established on solid foundations"—the famous "Tennis Court Oath." These events mark the formal beginning of the French Revolution.',
