    summaryEn: 'The peace treaty ending World War I imposed massive reparations and territorial losses on Germany, with its harsh terms widely regarded as one of the underlying causes of World War II.',
    description: '1919年6月28日，在巴黎凡尔赛宫的镜厅——1871年德意志帝国在此宣布成立的同一地点——德国代表被迫签署了《协约及参战各国对德和约》（通称《凡尔赛和约》）。条约要求德国割让13%的领土和所有海外殖民地，军队限制在10万人以内，禁止拥有空军和潜艇，更为严酷的是，第231条（"战争罪责条款"）单独将战争责任归咎于德国及其盟友，并据此要求支付天文数字的战争赔款（后定为1320亿金马克）。虽然美国总统威尔逊的"十四点"计划推动了国际联盟的建立，但美国参议院最终拒绝批准和约，美国也未曾加入国联。赔款负担和"背后一刀"的羞辱感成为纳粹党煽动复仇情绪的有力武器。',
    descriptionEn: 'On June 28, 1919, in the Hall of Mirrors at the Palace of Versailles—the very room where the German Empire had been proclaimed in 1871—German representatives were forced to sign the Treaty of Peace between the Allied and Associated Powers and Germany. The treaty stripped Germany of 13% of its territory and all overseas colonies, limited its army to 100,000 men, and prohibited an air force and submarines. More devastatingly, Article 231 (the "war guilt clause") assigned sole responsibility for the war to Germany and its allies, justifying astronomical reparations (ultimately set at 132 billion gold marks). Though US President Wilson\'s "Fourteen Points" inspired the creation of the League of Nations, the US Senate refused to ratify the treaty and America never joined the League. The reparations burden and the humiliation of war guilt became potent tools for Nazi propaganda in fomenting revenge.',
