    summaryEn: 'The Allies established the International Military Tribunal to try Nazi war criminals, creating the precedent of individual criminal responsibility under international law.',
    description: '1945年11月20日至1946年10月1日，由美、英、法、苏四国法官组成的国际军事法庭在德国纽伦堡审判了24名纳粹德国最高级别的政治和军事领导人。被告被指控犯有反和平罪、战争罪和反人类罪——这三类罪名首次在国际法中被明确定义。12名被告被判处绞刑，7人获有期徒刑，3人无罪释放。纽伦堡审判确立了"上级命令不构成免责理由"和"反人类罪不受时效限制"等里程碑式的法律原则。1946-1949年间还进行了针对医生、法官、工业家等特定群体的12轮后续审判。尽管有人批评这是"胜利者的正义"，但纽伦堡审判为后来的前南斯拉夫国际刑事法庭、卢旺达国际刑事法庭和常设的国际刑事法院（ICC）奠定了法理基础。',
    descriptionEn: 'From November 20, 1945, to October 1, 1946, the International Military Tribunal, composed of judges from the United States, Britain, France, and the Soviet Union, tried 24 of Nazi Germany\'s highest-ranking political and military leaders in Nuremberg. The defendants faced charges of crimes against peace, war crimes, and crimes against humanity—the first time these three categories were explicitly defined in international law. Twelve defendants were sentenced to death by hanging, seven received prison terms, and three were acquitted. The Nuremberg Trials established landmark legal principles: "superior orders is no defense" and crimes against humanity have no statute of limitations. Twelve subsequent trials targeting specific groups (doctors, judges, industrialists) were conducted from 1946-1949. Despite criticism as "victors\' justice," Nuremberg laid the jurisprudential foundation for the later International Criminal Tribunals for the former Yugoslavia and Rwanda, and the permanent International Criminal Court (ICC).',
